<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=101168336719288></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f101168336719288><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=2&mid=101168336719288>RE: Newbie Questions</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=2&mid=101168336719288#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=73658><span id=Sage>DavivMcD</span></a>, <span id=Sage>Sage</span><br><span id=notbold>292 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Tue, Jan 22nd 3:10 AM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good<span id=notbold>[3.70]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>No problem, Roofshadow; glad I could help. Now for the answers:<br><br>1) If you fail the pickpocket (but the mob doesn't necessarily attack you) hide will turn off. I'm not sure if you remain hidden when you are successful, but in most cases you will probably fail once or twice before you get anything good. Don't be fooled by the hide button. If you are sneaking at the same time as hiding, there are only 2 things that will deselect the hide button: 1) Physically deselecting it, and 2) Deselecting sneak after you've moved a little. Anything else that will turn off hide but not sneak (looting corpses, doing a trade, unsuccessful pickpockets) will not show you anything to let you know you aren't hidden. Make sure you're really hidden by conning a mob that would usually have non-indifferent faction and that's facing you, or just be safe and un-hide/re-hide. Anyway, back to the topic at hand, as long as the mob doesn't attack you, pickpocket will NOT turn off sneak. This can be used to sneak behind KOS mobs, pickpocket, and still have a chance of remaining undetected if you fail.<br><br>2) Ditto on everyone else's answers. Although don't worry about your group noticing about the loot too much. It'll be a while until you can consistently steal enough to make other's worried. Also, I have never ever seen a mob I was pickpocketting get left with 1pp 1gp 1sp and 1cp or whatever. I'm pretty sure you can pickpocket pretty much all the cash off the mob, given you have enough time and chances to do it. I was just killin' some sarnaks in LOIO and I had stolen at least 1pp off a recruit while I was fighting it. When I looted it, it had only 2 or 3 copper left on it. Of course, this will probably just make your group even more suspicious of you. Oh and notice a theme with all the mobs slipskin listed that shout out when they catch you steal? They are all relatively more intelligent mobs. Orcs, on the other hand, are just too dumb to know what you're doing. They get mad because your hand's invading their personal space, not because you tried to steal. And I think I actually have PPed off undead and animals. It was in LOIO, where the sabretooths carry around the change of their last lunch.<br><br>3) Don't worry about contributing; grouping before level 13 is pretty much just for learning the game and finding friends (at least it was for me). No one really has much going on before lvl 10, so you might as well stick together.<br><br>4) The quickest and cheapest weapon upgrade you can do is to go to town and buy a sharpening stone at your local blacksmith's (should be less than 1pp). Now put the stone and your rusty dagger in a forge and combine to make a brand new tarnished rapier. Of course that's a pretty weak upgrade; for a more serious upgrade I suggest getting some better cash first. Everyone has their preferences and mine is east commonlands. It's pretty neat and organized and there's plenty of things to collect to make cash. The desert area has tons of skellies with tons of bone chips, pumas with the occaisional med or high quality cat pelt, and asps with those lovely asp venom sacks. Save em til lvl 18 when you can start applying poison (of coure you can't directly apply the sack to your weapon; you have to let toxdil process them for you), or just sell em. Then in the rest of the zone there are plenty of lions and wolves and bears (oh my! =P) with their corresponding quality skins. And the best part of all, the orc camps. Deathfist orcs are higher level than their faydwer cousins, but give much better xp and loot. DF belts generally sell to PC's for 3-5pp a piece, as opposed to 1-3pp for CB belts. Get a group at one of these camps and practice pickpocket, and you can make quite a steal. And trust me, your group won't notice a few belts missing; just make sure you don't let them know you're hoarding 20 belts when they only have 3. As an alternative to selling the belts, you can turn them in to Captain Hazran at the Freeport Militia House in West Freeport. Some advantages of this quest:<br>1) You only need one belt, but you can turn 4 in at a time and get 4 times the rewards.<br>2) Gives great faction with Freeport militia. It took at most 20 belts to go from dubious to amiable.<br>3) Gives great XP for your level. After a long day's work at the orc camps, turning in the day's belts gave me 1 or 2 extra YELLOW bubbles of XP.<br>4) Gives you decent cash back to replace the 3-5pp you coulda made selling it. Usually a random amount of gold.<br><br>Disadvantages:<br>1) Slightly lowers Knights of Truth (the Freeport paladins in N. FP) faction. However this usually doesn't affect anything, as just killing orcs improves faction with the Knights. If you still are worried about your faction, take a quick trip to the Hall of Truth in NFP. Swim around the moat and kill all the pirhanas (don't kill the minnows!). This will improve Knights faction without lowering Freeport Militia.<br>2) {This space for rent}<br><br>Well, I'm going to stop rambling now and get back into EQ. Good luck!<br>&nbsp;<br>Daviv McD 32nd Dwarf Rogue<br>Lords of Belterra<br>Xegony</td></tr>
