<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=101129719424508></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f101129719424508><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=2&mid=101129719424508>RE: rogue's</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=2&mid=101129719424508#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=73658><span id=Sage>DavivMcD</span></a>, <span id=Sage>Sage</span><br><span id=notbold>292 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Thu, Jan 17th 2:53 PM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good<span id=notbold>[4.13]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Nice tips, Ceiliron. I definitely agree with you on screwing the others and getting yourself out of trouble when things get hairy. It might piss a lot of people off, but I have two reasons for justifying it:<br><br>1) Role-playing, duh! When I played a paladin, I stayed no matter what, and lost several lives because of that. Now as a rogue, I can get my revenge and leave the other suckers to take the heat. The only exception to this conveniently follows role-playing as well; if I'm grouped with friends I'll most likely see what I can do to help everyone. I don't run until they say it's ok.<br><br>2) Corpse recovery. Ok, so you don't really help much in retrieving corpses if your group was in a common safe spot. But many times I found myself being relied as the only way to get corpses back. A couple of examples are when I grouped inside a fort, such as the LOIO sarnak fort or the mountain giant fort in Frontier Mtns, or in any type of raid situation gone wrong. During my quest for the burning rapier, I joined a rag-tag group of mid 30s hoping to successfully raid the mob I needed. Needless to say we got raped. At the first sign of trouble I immediately jumped back from the heat and hid. I kept offering to help recover corpses, but they had their plan with their invis-spells and ignored me because I was a lowly level 25. After they found out the hard way the mobs around the disaster site could see through invis, they finally agreed to let me help.<br><br>Edit: I forgot about evade. If you use this as often as possible, you will rarely see any problem with keeping aggro off you. A good way to do this is to make a macro that does backstab and evade, and make sure you keep using it in battle. I would also personally put pick-pocket in there. I PP as often as possible. This is another thing I never find problems about. First of all, if you're grouping with complete strangers you should definitely steal from them. It's just in a rogue's nature. Don't worry too much about not getting friends. By the time you can actually PP enough to endanger your relationships with group members, you should already have plenty of friends to fall back on. Which brings me to the second rule, don't PP from friends unless they're cool with it. Same with guildies. And if you have those friends and a decent guild, you have nothing to worry about from earning a bad reputation. Even if you get the rare flamer who'll shout out across the zone not to group with a thief like you, no one really ever listens to them. And if you are finding trouble getting a group, just send a tell to some friends or guildies and make your own.<br><br>Another edit: Just remembered something in Dadiella's post I wanted to comment on. If you're still having trouble keeping away from the mob's attacks, step back out of melee range, and start using thrown weapons. You might want to practice throwing a little if you haven't yet. They allow you to be quite flexible in battle and can actually do a decent amount of damage if you use them right.<br><br><em id=fs8>Edited, Thu Jan 17 15:12:50 2002</em><br>&nbsp;<br>Daviv McD 32nd Dwarf Rogue<br>Lords of Belterra<br>Xegony</td></tr>
